Balwhidder,â said I, âand I will yours for the sake of my lucky day.â

âMy name is not spoken,â she replied, with a great deal of haughtiness.
âMore than a hundred years it has not gone upon menâs tongues, save for a
blink.  I am nameless, like the Folk of Peace. {3}  Catriona Drummond is
the one I use.â

Now indeed I knew where I was standing.  In all broad Scotland there was
but the one name proscribed, and that was the name of the Macgregors.
Yet so far from fleeing this undesirable acquaintancy, I plunged the
deeper in.

âI have been sitting with one who was in the same case with yourself,â
said I, âand I think he will be one of your friends.  They called him
Robin Oig.â

âDid ye so?â cries she.  âYe met Rob?â

âI passed the night with him,â said I.

âHe is a fowl of the night,â said she.

âThere was a set of pipes there,â I went on, âso you may judge if the
time passed.â

âYou should be no enemy, at all events,â said she.  âThat was his brother
there a moment since, with the red soldiers round him.  It is him that I
call father.â

âIs it so?â cried I.  âAre you a daughter of James Moreâs?â

âAll the daughter that he has,â says she: âthe daughter of a prisoner;
that I should forget it so, even for one hour, to talk with strangers!â

Here one of the gillies addressed her in what he had of English, to know
what âsheâ (meaning by that himself) was to do about âta sneeshin.â  I
took some note of him for a short, bandy-legged, red-haired, big-headed
