likely stick at nothing; and that to fall by the sword, however
ungracefully, was still an improvement on the gallows.  I considered
besides that by the unguarded pertness of my words and the quickness of
my blow I had put myself quite out of court; and that even if I ran, my
adversary would probably pursue and catch me, which would add disgrace to
my misfortune.  So that, taking all in all, I continued marching behind
him, much as a man follows the hangman, and certainly with no more hope.

We went about the end of the long craigs, and came into the Hunterâs Bog.
Here, on a piece of fair turf, my adversary drew.  There was nobody there
to see us but some birds; and no resource for me but to follow his
example, and stand on guard with the best face I could display.  It seems
it was not good enough for Mr. Dancansby, who spied some flaw in my
manÅuvres, paused, looked upon me sharply, and came off and on, and
menaced me with his blade in the air.  As I had seen no such proceedings
from Alan, and was besides a good deal affected with the proximity of
