âCatriona?â said I.  It seemed that was the first and last word of my
eloquence.

âYou will be glad to see me again?â says she.

âAnd I think that is an idle word,â said I.  âWe are too deep friends to
make speech upon such trifles.â

âIs she not the girl of all the world?â she cried again.  âI was never
knowing such a girl so honest and so beautiful.â

âAnd yet she cared no more for Alpin than what she did for a kale-stock,â
said I.

âAh, she will say so indeed!â cries Catriona.  âYet it was for the name
and the gentle kind blood that she took me up and was so good to me.â

âWell, I will tell you why it was,â said I.  âThere are all sorts of
peopleâs faces in this world.  There is Barbaraâs face, that everyone
must look at and admire, and think her a fine, brave, merry girl.  And
then there is your face, which is quite differentâI never knew how
different till to-day.  You cannot see yourself, and that is why you do
not understand; but it was for the love of your face that she took you up
and was so good to you.  And everybody in the world would do the same.â

âEverybody?â says she.

âEvery living soul!â said I.

âAh, then, that will be why the soldiers at the castle took me up!â she
cried.

âBarbara has been teaching you to catch me,â said I.

âShe will have taught me more than that at all events.  She will have
